{{Chembox | ImageFile = 1-Methylpyridinium.svg | ImageSize = 80px | IUPACName = 1-Methylpyridinium | OtherNames = ''N''-Methylpyridinium |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo = 694-56-4 | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|}} | PubChem = 13597 | ChemSpiderID = 13008 | SMILES = [n+]1(ccccc1)C | InChI = 1/C6H8N/c1-7-5-3-2-4-6-7/h2-6H,1H3/q+1 | InChIKey = PQBAWAQIRZIWIV-UHFFFAOYAW | StdInChI = 1S/C6H8N/c1-7-5-3-2-4-6-7/h2-6H,1H3/q+1 | StdInChIKey = PQBAWAQIRZIWIV-UHFFFAOYSA-N }} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | Formula = C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>8</sub>N<sup>+</sup> | MolarMass = 94.134 g/mol | Appearance = | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} |Section3={{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Methylpyridinium''' is a chemical compound which is the [[quaternary ammonium compound]] derived from the ''N''-[[methylation]] of [[pyridine]]. It is found in some [[coffee]] products.<ref name="ScienceDaily">{{cite web | url= https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2003/10/031015031251.htm | title= Highly Active Compound Found In Coffee May Prevent Colon Cancer | publisher= ScienceDaily | date= Oct 15, 2003 | accessdate = 2012 }}</ref> It is not present in unroasted coffee beans, but is formed during roasting from its precursor chemical, [[trigonelline]].<ref name="ScienceDaily" /> It is under investigation by scientists regarding its potential [[anti-carcinogenic]] properties,<ref name="Coffees rich">{{cite journal | pmid = 21448860 | year = 2011 | last1 = Boettler | first1 = U | last2 = Volz | first2 = N | last3 = Pahlke | first3 = G | last4 = Teller | first4 = N | last5 = Kotyczka | first5 = C | last6 = Somoza | first6 = V | last7 = Stiebitz | first7 = H | last8 = Bytof | first8 = G | last9 = Lantz | first9 = I | last10 = Lang | first10 = Roman | last11 = Hofmann | first11 = Thomas | last12 = Marko | first12 = Doris | title = Coffees rich in chlorogenic acid or N-methylpyridinium induce chemopreventive phase II-enzymes via the Nrf2/ARE pathway in vitro and in vivo | volume = 55 | issue = 5 | pages = 798–802 | doi = 10.1002/mnfr.201100115 | journal = Molecular Nutrition & Food Research | display-authors = 8 }}</ref> particularly an effect on [[colon cancer]].<ref name="ScienceDaily" />
==Ionic liquid==
The chloride of N-methylpyridinium behaves as an [[ionic liquid]] in the molten state. Its properties with different mixtures of [[zinc chloride]] have been characterised by several authors in the temperature range 150 – 200&nbsp;°C (423 – 473 K).<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Simonis | first1 = L. | last2 = Coppe | first2 = C. | last3 = Glibert | first3 = J. | last4 = Claes | first4 = P. | year = 1986 | title = Properties of mixtures of zinc chloride and N-methylpyridinium chloride in the molten state – I. Phase diagram and heats of mixing | doi = 10.1016/0040-6031(86)85285-6 | journal = Thermochimica Acta | volume = 99 | issue = | pages = 223–232 }}</ref><sup>, </sup><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Claes | first1 = P. | last2 = Simonis | first2 = L. | last3 = Glibert | first3 = J. | year = 1986 | title = Properties of mixtures of zinc chloride and N-methylpyridinium chloride in the molten state – II. Specific mass, electrical conductivity and viscosity | doi = 10.1016/0013-4686(86)87071-2 | journal = Electrochimica Acta | volume = 31 | issue = 12| pages = 1525–1530 }}</ref><sup>, </sup><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Claes | first1 = P. F. | last2 = Coppe | first2 = C. R. | last3 = Simonis | first3 = L. A. | last4 = Glibert | first4 = J. E. | year = 1987 | title = Properties of mixtures of zinc chloride and N-methylpyridinium chloride in the molten state – III. Solubility of hydrogen chloride under atmospheric pressure and comparison with zinc chloride - N-ethylpyridinium bromide mixtures | doi = 10.1021/je00047a020 | journal = Journal of Chemical and Engineering Data | volume = 32 | issue = 1| pages = 70–72 }}</ref><sup>, </sup><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Marković | first1 = R. | last2 = Minić | first2 = D. M. | year = 1997 | title = Conductometric and thermal studies of fused Zn (II) salts containing methyl substituted pyridinium cations | doi = 10.1016/S0254-0584(97)80178-2 | journal = Materials Chemistry and Physics | volume = 50 | issue = 1| pages = 20–24 }}</re