{{unreferenced|date=September 2011}} {{Infobox city Japan |name = Sakuma |native_name = 佐久間町 |settlement_type = Former municipality |image_skyline = |image_caption = |image_map = Map.Sakuma.Shizuoka.PNG |image_flag = Flag of Sakuma Shizuoka.jpg |image_symbol = Sakuma Shizuoka chapter.png |region = [[Chūbu region|Chūbu]] ([[Tōkai region|Tōkai]]) |prefecture = [[Shizuoka Prefecture]] |district = [[Iwata District, Shizuoka|Iwata]] |merged = July 1, 2005 |merged_into = [[Hamamatsu, Shizuoka|Hamamatsu]] |area_km2 = 168.53 |population_as_of = June 1, 2005 |population = 5,394 |density_km2 = 32 |coordinates = {{coord|35.090452|N|137.80602|E|region:JP|display=inline,title}} |tree = ''[[Cryptomeria]]'' |flower = [[Azalea]] |bird = [[Japanese white-eye]] |website = |footnotes = }}
{{nihongo|'''Sakuma'''|佐久間町|Sakuma-chō}} was a [[List of towns in Japan|town]] located in [[Iwata District, Shizuoka|Iwata District]], [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], [[Japan]].
At the time of its merger, the town had an estimated [[population]] of 5,394 and a [[population density|density]] of 32 persons per km<sup>2</sup>. The total area was 168.53&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.
On July 1, 2005, Sakuma, along with the cities of [[Tenryū, Shizuoka|Tenryū]] and [[Hamakita, Shizuoka|Hamakita]], the town of [[Haruno, Shizuoka|Haruno]] (from [[Shūchi District, Shizuoka|Shūchi District]]), the towns of [[Hosoe, Shizuoka|Hosoe]], [[Inasa, Shizuoka|Inasa]] and [[Mikkabi, Shizuoka|Mikkabi]] (all from [[Inasa District, Shizuoka|Inasa District]]), the town of [[Misakubo, Shizuoka|Misakubo]], the village of [[Tatsuyama, Shizuoka|Tatsuyama]] (all from [[Iwata District, Shizuoka|Iwata District]]), and the towns of [[Maisaka, Shizuoka|Maisaka]] and [[Yūtō, Shizuoka|Yūtō]] (both from [[Hamana District, Shizuoka|Hamana District]]), was merged into the expanded city of [[Hamamatsu, Shizuoka|Hamamatsu]], and is now part of [[Tenryū-ku, Hamamatsu|Tenryū-ku]], Hamamatsu City.
Sakuma is the location of the [[Sakuma Dam]], an important [[hydroelectric]] power plant, and a [[frequency converter]] station that permits exchange of power between Japan's two different [[utility frequency|power systems]]. Japan's grids are also connected by two other stations, located at [[Higashi-Shimizu Frequency Converter|Higashi-Shimizu]] and [[Shin Shinano Frequency Converter Station|Shin Shinano]].
