{{chembox | Verifiedfields = changed | verifiedrevid = 441066916 | ImageFile = TiC-xtal-3D-vdW.png | ImageSize = | IUPACName = | OtherNames = |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}} | CASNo = 12070-08-5 | PubChem = | SMILES = }} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | Formula = TiC | MolarMass = 59.89 g/mol | Appearance = black powder | Density = 4.93 g/cm<sup>3</sup> | MeltingPtC = 3160 | BoilingPtC = 4820 | Solubility = insoluble in [[water]] | MagSus = +8.0·10<sup>−6</sup> cm<sup>3</sup>/mol }} |Section3={{Chembox Structure | CrystalStruct = [[Sodium Chloride|Cubic]], [[Pearson symbol|cF8]] | SpaceGroup = Fm<u style="text-decoration:overline">3</u>m, No. 225 | Coordination = Octahedral }} |Section7={{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Titanium carbide''', [[Titanium|Ti]][[Carbon|C]], is an extremely [[hardness|hard]] ([[Mohs scale of mineral hardness|Mohs]] 9–9.5) [[refractory]] [[ceramic]] material, similar to [[tungsten carbide]]. It has the appearance of black powder with the [[sodium chloride]] ([[Cubic crystal system#Rock-salt structure|face-centered cubic]]) [[crystal structure]]. As found in nature its crystals range in size from 0.1 to 0.3mm.
Titanium carbide is used in preparation of [[cermet]]s, which are frequently used to [[machining|machine]] [[steel]] materials at high cutting speed. It is also used as an abrasion-resistant surface coating on metal parts, such as [[tool bit]]s and watch mechanisms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eduloc.com/products/511.html|title=Titanium carbide TiC powder cas 12070-08-5|last=|first=|date=|website=www.eduloc.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Titanium carbide is also used as a [[heat shield]] coating for [[atmospheric reentry]] of [[spacecraft]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sforza|first1=Pasquale M.|title=Manned Spacecraft Design Principles|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=ntWcBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA406&ots=i1g3SbIaAy&dq=titanium%20carbide%20heat%20shield&hl=fr&pg=PA406#v=onepage&q=titanium%20carbide&f=false|publisher=Elsevier|accessdate=4 January 2017|page=406|language=en|date=13 November 2015}}</ref>
It occurs in nature as a form of the very rare mineral ''{{Interlanguage link|khamrabaevite|en|Khamrabaevite|it|Khamrabaevite|WD=}}'' ({{Lang-ru|Хамрабаевит}}) - (Ti,V,Fe)C. It was discovered in 1984 on Mount Arashan in the Chatkal District,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dunn|first1=Pete J|title=New mineral names|journal= American Mineralogist|date=1985|volume=70|pages=1329–1335|url=|accessdate=}}</ref> USSR (modern [[Kyrgyzstan]]), near the Uzbek border. The mineral was named after Ibragim Khamrabaevich Khamrabaev, director of Geology and Geophysics of [[Tashkent]], [[Uzbekistan]].
==Physical properties== Titanium carbide has an [[elastic modulus]] of approximately 400 GPa and a shear modulus of 188 GPa.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://scitation.aip.org/content/aip/journal/jap/37/10/10.1063/1.1707923 |title=Low‐Temperature Elastic Properties of ZrC and TiC |last=Chang |first=R |last2=Graham |first2=L |date=1966 |journal=Applied Physics |publisher= |volume=37|pages=3778 |doi=10.1063/1.1707923}}</ref>
==Manufacturing and machining==
Tool bits without tungsten content can be made of titanium carbide in [[nickel]]-cobalt matrix [[cermet]], enhancing the cutting speed, precision, and smoothness of the workpiece.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}
The resistance to [[wear]], [[corrosion]], and [[oxidation]] of a [[tungsten carbide]]–[[cobalt]] material can be increased by adding 6–30% of titanium carbide to tungsten carbide. This forms a [[solid solution]] that is more [[brittleness|brittle]] and susceptible to breakage.{{clarify|reason=why would that be an advantage?|date=July 2015}}
Titanium carbide can be [[Etching|etched]] with [[reactive-ion etching]].
