[[File:Radar image of the 2011 Joplin tornado May 22, 2011 2248Z.png|thumb|300px|On the left, a typical debris ball shown as an area of high reflectivity on the end of the [[hook echo]] of the parent [[supercell]] of the [[2011 Joplin tornado]] co-located with a velocity couplet on the right|alt=Image showing two radar images. On the left is a base reflectivity radar image, which displays precipitation. On the right is a storm relative velocity radar image, which shows direction and intensity of wind speeds.]] A '''tornadic debris signature''' ('''TDS'''), often colloquially referred to as a '''debris ball''',<ref name=tdsapr27>{{cite web|title=Radar Tornadic Debris Signatures on 27&nbsp;April&nbsp;2011|url=http://www.crh.noaa.gov/Image/unr/soo/scm/2011-ION1.pdf|publisher=National Weather Service|accessdate=31 December 2012|author=Bunkers, Matthew J.|author2=Baxter, Martin A.|date=August 23, 2011}}</ref> is an area of high [[reflectivity]] on [[weather radar]] caused by [[debris]] lofting into the air, usually associated with a [[tornado]].<ref name=tdsapr27 /><ref name=tallahasseewfo>{{cite web|title=Severe Weather & Flooding Event of March 3, 2012; Lowndes-Lanier Co. EF3 Tornado|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/tae/?n=event-20120303-severewx|publisher=National Weather Service|accessdate=31 December 2012|location=[[Tallahassee, Florida]]}}</ref> A TDS may also be indicated by dual-polarization [[Pulse-Doppler radar|radar]] products, designated as a '''polarimetric tornado debris signature''' ('''PTDS'''). Polarimetric radar can discern meteorological and nonmeteorological [[hydrometeor]]s and the co-location of a PTDS with the enhanced reflectivity of a debris ball are used by meteorologists as confirmation that a tornado is occurring.<ref>{{cite web |title = Tornadic Debris Signature from Dual Polarization Radar |publisher = NWS Birmingham, AL |date = October 3, 2012 |url = http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=weatherreview_1001 |accessdate = 2014-05-12 |archiveurl = |archivedate = }}</ref>
==Background== [[File:Debris Ball Radar Products.jpg|thumb|left|Comparison of four radar products: reflectivity, Z, top left; velocity, SRM, top right; and polarimetric products, differential reflectivity, Z<sub>DR</sub>, on bottom left; correlation coefficient, CC, on bottom right, used to identify TDSs]] Debris balls can be a result of [[Human impact on the environment|anthropogenic]] or [[biomass]] debris and are more likely to occur if a tornado crosses a "target-rich" environment such as a forest or populated area. A TDS is most likely to be observed when a tornado is closer to a radar site and the farther away from the radar that a TDS is observed the more likely that the tornado is stronger. As a result of the strong [[wind]]s required to damage structures and loft debris into the air, debris balls are normally the result of EF3 or stronger tornadoes on the [[Enhanced Fujita Scale]]. Weaker tornadoes may also not cause debris balls due to their mostly short-lived nature and thus any debris may not be sampled by radar.<ref name=jointpol>{{cite journal|last=Ryzhkov|first=Alexander V.|author2=Schuur, Terry J. |author3=Burgess, Donald W. |author4=Heinselman, Pamela L. |author5=Giangrande, Scott E. |author6= Zrnic, Dusan S. |title=The Joint Polarization Experiment: Polarimetric Rainfall Measurements and Hydrometeor Classification|journal=Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc.|year=2005|volume=86|issue=6|pages=809–24 [821]|doi=10.1175/BAMS-86-6-809|url=http://www.research.noaa.gov/research/papers07/jpole.pdf|accessdate=31 December 2012|bibcode = 2005BAMS...86..809R }}</ref> However, not all tornadoes meeting such strength requirements exhibit debris balls, depending on their vicinity to sources of debris and distance from the radar site.<ref name=tdsapr27 /> A debris ball on radar images can verify tornadoes 70–80% of the time.<ref name=learningdebrisball>{{cite web|title=Learning About Weather Radar ... The Debris Ball|url=http://fox41blogs.typepad.com/wdrb_weather/2012/03/learning-about-weather-radar-the-debris-ball.html|publisher=WDRB.com|accessdate=31 December 2012|author=Weinberg, Marc|date=March 19, 2012}}</ref>
Debris balls are seen on radar reflectivity images as a small, roundish area of high reflectivity values. Research conducted on debris balls that were noted during the [[2011 Super Outbreak]] suggested that horizontal reflectivity from debris balls ranged from 51 to 72 [[dBZ (meteorology)|dBZ]] during those outbreaks. Reflectivity values also decreased with increasing height.<ref name=tdsapr27 /> Due to the irregular and variable size, shapes, and tumbling nature of tornadic debris, debris balls typically produce a [[Weather radar#Polarization|correlation coefficient]] (''ρ<sub>hv</sub>'') less than 0.80. Differential reflectivity (''Z<sub>DR</sub>'') values associated with debris balls are normally near or below 0&nbsp;dB. Debris balls are almost always associated with a strong velocity couplet and the corresponding algorithm based detection, the [[tornado vortex signature]] (TVS) or tornado detection algorithm (TDA).<ref name=tdslesson>{{cite web|title=Dual-Pol Radar Applications: Tornadic Debris Signatures|url=http://www.wdtb.noaa.gov/courses/dualpol/Applications/TDS/player.html|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=31 December 2012|author=Schlatter, Paul}}</ref> {{clear}}
